title: For Sale:  Rossi Youth Combo .22 LR / 20 Ga.
location: Grey Forest (NW of SA), San Antonio, Texas
postcontent:
Rossi youth combo, .22 LR / 20 Ga., both barrels included. My nephews outgrew it and are ready for something bigger. This is just the right size for a youngster, with a shortened stock and comb reduced for smaller hands. It's heavy enough to earn their respect and tame the recoil, but not so much that they'll have trouble handling it.

Includes synthetic sling with Uncle Mike's quick release on one end. Nice wood stock and fore end with some light handling marks. White outline buttplate. Thumbsaver installed on the hammer makes it easier and more comfortable to handle. Transfer bar and hammer block manual safeties. Changing barrels is simply a matter of unscrewing the front sling swivel to remove the forearm.

Both barrels are in excellent condition, near-100% finish on the outside and bright and clean on the inside. The shotgun barrel is a 22" 20 gauge 3" modified choke with a front bead. The rifle barrel is a 18½" .22 LR, so of course it could also be used for .22 L or .22 S – very handy for a new shooter. It has removable standard front blade and rear notch sights installed, but is also drilled and tapped for a scope mount.

Here's the info from the Rossi web site:

The youth size Rossi Matched Pair makes the perfect first gun for teaching that young hunter in your life how to safely shoot and hunt. All offer a smaller stock and barrel to ensure that the first time out is a pleasant experience. Single shot has long been recognized as the best teaching firearm for young shooters and Rossi adds in transfer bar technology to help prevent accidental discharges as well as a manual safety. Blued 18-1/2" .22 LR rifle barrel and 22" 20 gauge shotgun barrel. Wood stock.

title: For Sale:  WASR 10/63 AK 47 7.62x39
postcontent:
I have a factory only fired Romanian WASR 10/63 AK 7.62x39 for sale.  This rifle still has some cosmoline on it.  This is the best example of a Wasr 10/63 that I have seen.  It was hand selected out of a shipment of 25 rifles that were also hand selected for quality.  The Wasr 10/63 is the premium of the Wasr AK rifles.  These are not made from the military reject parts like the Wasr 10's are, but are made from actual demilled Romanian Military rifles in Romania on new Romanian receivers with new Romanian cold hammer forged and chrome lined barrels.  Most of these like this one came from National Guard type semi-auto only rifles that rarely saw use.  The receiver has a factory rail on the side for mounting optics.  The date on the trunnion is 1970 and has the military triangle with the arrow in it.

This rifle barrel is threaded and has a slant brake, cleaning rod, and cleaning kit in the buttstock, and Romanian leather sling.  The bayonet lug is intact so you can affix a bayonet if you like.  It has a factory installed Tapco G2 trigger set for 922r compliance.  It will come with a Tapco bakelite colored 30 round magazine as well as the box, manual, and plastic oil bottle.  Included is also a Romanian metal military magazine that was included, but is beat up and non functional.  It came with the rifle but I kept it for parts.

I am asking 700 dollars for this excellent example of a WASR 10/63.

Authentic civil war cavalry officer's saber made by Henry Boker of Solingen Germany, who was a blade maker during the civil war, and was known to make swords for both the north and the south. It is of a fairly rare maker mark.  Herman Boker (Henry's brother) was the founder of "Boker & Co." Cutlery in New York and imported his brother's swords in support of the civil war. title: For Sale/Trade:  12 Gauge 1 oz Slugs. Really. They're Free.
postcontent:
I don't have a slug gun. I never have time to hunt deer during gun week. I only ever shot one animal with a slug.  I loaded a slug into the chamber by mistake and took a shot at a rabbit.  

I don't know what happened to the boxes or the 10th round.  I am giving these items away in the hope that somebody will harvest some deer with them this (or next) season.  It isn't need based.  They're something that takes up room and gets in the way.  I keep having to move them.  I would rather move them into someone's possession who is going to put them to good use.

Update: I found the 10th round.  This is now an offer of 2 boxes worth of FREE 12 gauge slugs.  Just drop me a note.  

I ask that anybody who responds is legal to own firearms and can legally be in possession of ammunition.  If you look under age, I'll want to see your picture ID (just the photo and birth date).

I have 
5 Winchester Super-X 2 3/4" 1 oz hollow point slugs
and 
5 Federal Maximum HI-Shok 2 3/4" hollow point slugs (they don't state 1 oz, but I weighed 
them on a digital scale and they register the same as the Winchesters)

I don't remember if they're rifled slugs (for a smooth barrel) or smooth slugs (for a rifled barrel).

They're free if you want them.  I will accept 1 appointment per day to meet and give you the ammo.  (I am doing this so nobody is on their way to get these when I am meeting someone else for the same purpose. In other words, I don't want anybody to waste a trip).

If you feel like trading me something, feel free.  I shoot 9mm (and will begin reloading soon), so a little brass would be nice. a box of .22 lr is always welcome (I have kids who like to go plinkin'. Then again, aren't we all just big kids who like to go plinkin'?).  As these are not worth a lot, I wouldn't ask for more.  You don't have to have something to trade in order to receive these.  It's strictly First Come, First Served.  

As these things are free, I'm not inclined to drive to a meeting with you, but if you live between London & Delaware, I drive that route twice a day, so I can make a stop or a brief detour pretty easily.  I am at home, in London, today and I will be at work in Delaware tomorrow.  If you're going to be one of those two places, it's free ammo.  If I don't get a response by the end of gun week, I'll cut them open and put the projectiles in the smelting pot.  It just seems a bit of a waste, if somebody could use them.

I am always in the market for pistol and shotgun powder and shot. I will begin reloading metallic rifle cartridges soon, too.  If you have any supplies for those endeavors, I'd like to discuss prices for those items with you.
